commitResults.messageBody:
Uses a text file to store the task list created during usage of the
program. Allows for task list to be reused after closing the program

commitResults.messageTitle: Use LocalDate and LocalTime instead of Strings for TimedTasks
commitResults.messageBody:
Deadline and Event tasks now use LocalDate which is compulsory and
LocalTime which is optional (set to null by default) instead of a
String to encapsulate the deadline timing

commitResults.messageTitle: Add javafx and small changes to logic flow
commitResults.messageBody:
Changed the logic flow of storage. Creating an instance of Storage now
creates the storage file at the given path if it does not exist.

Changed the logic flow of NonTimedCommand

Parts of code rely on certain arguments being exclusively one or two
values.

The arguments being inputted could potentially be outside the range of
intended arguments.

Use assertions to ensure that only the intended arguments are inputted.

Let's add assertions to ensure only intended arguments are the ones
that were inputted to reduce the number of bugs.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove code duplication by adding to parent class
commitResults.messageBody:
The getStorageDescription method duplicates code 3 times in the ToDo,
Deadline and Event class.

Deadline and Event classes both have a LocalTime variable in it.

Declaring a LocalTime variable in the TimedTask class as well as
implementing the getStorageDescription method in both Task and TimedTask
can reduce the amount of code duplication.

Let's create a LocalTime variable in the TimedTask class as well as
implement a getStorageDescription method in both the Task and TimedTask
classes.

This allows us to initialize less variables in Deadline and Event as
well as use the implementation of getStorageDescription in the parent
classes to implement the getStorageDescription method in ToDo, Deadline
and Event.

No undo feature to undo unwanted commands.

Having an undo feature allows users to undo an unwanted command.

Add an undo feature to allow users to undo the previous command that
edited the task list. If undo is inputted after an undo, the second undo
undoes the first undo (i.e. inputting "mark 1", "undo" and "undo" will
mark the 1st task as finished.).

Undo allows the latest command to be undone and if undo was the
unwanted command, undo can be inputted again to undo the undo command.
